What's the Current Best Computer Science Job?¶

Introduction¶

As a first-year Computer Science (CS) major, I want to know more about the current CS job scheme. This project analyzes recent CS job salary data to figure out the best CS jobs to pursue. In context, I define success based on 1) popularity, how common the job is, and 2) salary, how much the job pays. I use the 'AI, ML, Data Science Salary (2020- 2025)' dataset from Kaggle, which contains salary and Employment trends in AI, ML, and Data Science from the past 5 years.

Set Up¶

Before I manipulate the dataset, I want to set up my code, filter out irrelevant data, and visualize the raw data.

Visualize Raw Data¶

Description: Before I do anything, I want to visualize the data and see where jobs lie based on popularity and salary. I create a function k_means_clustering() that takes in 2 features and the number of desired clusters, applies k-mean clustering based on those features, and outputs the results on a scatter plot. I run the function using salary and popularity as features with 3 clusters.

Analysis: The first cluster has the lowest salaries and lowest popularities, the second cluster has the middle salaries and highest popularities, and the third cluster has the highest salaries and the middle popularities. I probably want a job in either the second or third cluster.

In [539]:
def k_means_clustering(feature1, feature2, k):
    """ Applies k-means clustering to dataset

    Args:
        feature1 (String): first feature k-means clustering will base on
        feature2 (String): second feature k-means clustering will base on
        k (integer): number of clusters
    """
    
    #get counts for each specific job
    counter = Counter(df['job_title'])
    sorted_counter = dict(sorted(counter.items()))

    #create a temporary data frame to store the popularity and mean salary for each job
    temp_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['popularity', 'salary'])
    temp_df['popularity'] = sorted_counter.values()
    temp_df['salary'] = df.groupby("job_title")["salary"].mean().values
    
    #select features
    X = temp_df[[feature1, feature2]].values

    #store labels and centroids
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init='k-means++', random_state=42, n_init='auto')
    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(X)
    centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_
    
    #output results (scatter plot)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=labels, cmap='viridis', s=50, alpha=0.7, label="Jobs")
    plt.scatter(centroids[:, 0], centroids[:, 1], c='red', marker='X', s=200, label='Centroids')
    plt.xlabel(f"{feature1}")
    plt.ylabel(f"{feature2}")
    plt.title(f"k‑Means Clustering (k={k})")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True, linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)
    plt.show()

#apply k-means clustering on salary and popularity with 3 clusters
k_means_clustering('salary', 'popularity', 3)

def popularity_summary_statistics(job_column):
    """ Outputs popularity statistics for given job column via text, bar graphs, and pie charts

    Args:
        job_column (list): list of jobs

    Return:
        list: 10 most common jobs
    """
    #store the counts of each job
    counter = Counter(job_column)
    
    #store top 10 most common jobs
    top_10_common_jobs = counter.most_common(10)
    jobs = [x for x,_ in top_10_common_jobs]
    counts = [x for _,x in top_10_common_jobs]

    #output results (text)
    print("10 most common jobs: ")
    for job, count in top_10_common_jobs:
        print(f'{job} appears {count} times')
    print()

    #output results (bar graph)
    plt.bar(jobs,counts)
    plt.title("10 Most Common Jobs")
    plt.xticks(rotation=90, ha="right")
    plt.xlabel("Jobs")
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    #output results (pie chart)
    plt.pie(counts,labels=jobs)
    plt.title("10 Most Common Jobs")
    plt.xlabel("Jobs")
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    #return top 10 most common jobs
    return list(jobs)

def salary_summary_statistics(jobs, top_k):
    """ Gives summary statistics for top k given jobs via boxplots

    Args:
        jobs (list): top most common jobs
        top_k (int): how many top jobs you want to analyze
    """
    #stores the salaries for specific jobs
    job_salaries = []
    
    #get the salaries for the top k jobs
    for i in range(top_k):
        job_salaries.append(df[(df["general_job_title"] == jobs[i]) | (df["job_title"] == jobs[i])]["salary"])
        
    #output results on one boxplot
    plt.boxplot(job_salaries, tick_labels = jobs[:top_k])
    plt.title(f"Summary Statistics for {jobs[:3]} Jobs")
    plt.xlabel('Job')
    plt.ylabel('Salary')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

#get salary statistics for top 3 general jobs
salary_summary_statistics(top_10_general_jobs, 3)

Remove Outliers & Identify Highest Paying Jobs¶

Description: Now that we've narrowed the general jobs down, I want to identify the highest-paying jobs for engineers and scientists. I noticed a lot of outliers in the boxplots, which might skew the data, particularly the means. Therefore, I created a helper function remove_outliers() that takes in a column name, data frame, lower and upper decimal representing dataset percentage and gets rid of outliers by returning the middle (upper - lower) percent. (Then, I created a function highest_paying_jobs() that takes in a general job and a number representing the top jobs I want to analyze and returns the top k highest-paying specific jobs based on their overall salary mean. I focus on the top 3 highest paying Engineer and Scientist jobs and also output respective boxplots.

Analysis: At first glance of the box plots, the means are very similar. Machine Learning Model Engineers only make around \$10,000 more than Research Scientists, Platform Engineers make around \$1000 less than Machine Learning Scientists, and a Machine Learning Engineer only makes around \$4000 more than an Applied Scientist. It's interesting to note that 3/6 jobs relate to Machine Learning. The box plots are also relatively similar. Therefore, I want to conduct further data analysis and predict future salary trends.

In [549]:
def remove_outliers(column_name, df, lower, upper):
    """ Remove outliers from specified column in specified dataset using interquartile range

    Args:
        column_name (String): name of column you want to remove outliers from
        df (Data Frame): data frame from which you want to remove outliers
        lower (float): lower percent you don't want to include
        upper (float): upper percent you don't want to include

    Return:
        Data Frame: updated dataframe with outliers removed
    """
    #lower quartile
    Q1 = df[column_name].quantile(lower)
    #upper quartile
    Q3 = df[column_name].quantile(upper)
    #spread of middle (upper - lower) percent of data set
    range = Q3 - Q1
    #lower bound
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * range
    #upper bound
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * range
    #return dataframe without outliers
    return df[(df["salary"] >= lower_bound) & (df["salary"] <= upper_bound)]

def highest_paying_jobs(job, top_k):
    """ calculates the top k highest-paying specific jobs based on their overall salary mean.

    Args:
        job (String): general job you want to find the top k highest salary specific jobs
        top_k (int): number of highest-salary-specific jobs you want

    Return:
        list: top k jobs
    """
    #dataframe for specified job with removed outliers
    job_df = remove_outliers("salary", df[df["general_job_title"] == job], .25, .75)
    
    #average salary for each job
    salaries = job_df.groupby("job_title")["salary"].mean()
    
    #zip and highest paying jobs and their salaries
    highest_paying_jobs = zip(salaries.index, salaries.values)

    #sort highest paying jobs and their salaries
    highest_paying_jobs = sorted(highest_paying_jobs, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    
    #output results for top k jobs
    print(f"Top {top_k} {job} Jobs: ")
    for job, salary in highest_paying_jobs[:top_k]:
        print(f"{job} gets paid an average of ${salary:.2f}")
    print()
        
    #return top k jobs
    return [x[0] for x in highest_paying_jobs[:top_k]]

Salary Linear Regression¶

Description: I want to predict the future salaries for the top 3 paying Engineer and Scientist jobs using a linear regression model. To do so, I create a function salary_linear_regression() that takes in the top k jobs to fit a linear model on the salary data and create models for Engineers and Scientists. To remove outliers, I used the interquartile range.

Analysis: Despite getting rid of outliers, the R^2 values are really low, meaning that the line doesn't fit the data well. This shows that even within high-paying jobs, there's a lot of salary variation. It also shows that I'm using a complex data set. There are not as many data points as I would've liked, with some years only having a few points. This specific dataset seems to have the most data from 2024. However, we can still visualize salary trends over time. The salaries for both years increase over time. Engineers have an edge with a slightly higher slope of 11225.72, meaning that the top 3 Engineer salaries are increasing by an average of \$11,225.72 per year.

In [552]:
def salary_linear_regression(top_k_jobs, lower, upper):
    """ fits a linear model on salary data

    Args:
        top_k_jobs (list): jobs you want to add to the linear regression model
        lower (float): lower percent you don't want to include
        upper (float): upper percent you don't want to include
    """
    #get the dataframe for the top k jobs
    top_k_df = remove_outliers("salary", df[df["job_title"].isin(top_k_jobs)], lower, upper)
    
    #store x and y values
    X = top_k_df["work_year"].values.reshape(-1, 1)
    Y = top_k_df["salary"].values
    
    #fit linear regression model
    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X, Y)
    
    #get parameters
    slope = model.coef_[0]
    intercept = model.intercept_
    Y_pred = model.predict(X)
    r_squared = r2_score(Y, Y_pred)
    
    #output results
    print(f"Slope: {slope:.2f}, Intercept: {intercept:.2f}, R²: {r_squared:.4f}")

    #plot linear model
    plt.scatter(X, Y, color="blue", label="Actual Data")
    plt.plot(X, Y_pred, color="red", linewidth=2, label="Regression Line")
    plt.xlabel("Work Year")
    plt.ylabel("Salary")
    plt.title(f"Work Year vs. {top_k_jobs[0].split(" ")[-1]} Salary (Linear Regression)")
    plt.legend()
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.show()

#get linear model for top 3 engineers
salary_linear_regression(top_3_engineers, .25, .75)

#get linear model for top 3 scientists
salary_linear_regression(top_3_scientists, .25, .75)

Weighted Sums¶

Description: The linear regression model was useful but maybe not the best metric for fitting the data. Therefore, I decided to find an alternate method to analyze the top 3 highest paying jobs: weighted sums. I created a function weighted_sums() that takes in the top k jobs, popularity weight, salary weight, and graph color to calculate and plot the weighted sums on histograms. I played around with different weight vectors, which control the importance of the popularity and salary. I tested 3 different scenarios: 1) popularity and salary are equally important 2) popularity is significantly more important, and 3) salary is significantly more important.

Analysis: This analysis gave me a much clearer picture of Engineers vs Scientists. Engineers tended to have higher weighted sums. Within the Engineer jobs, the Machine Learning Engineer had the most normal distribution, number of data points, and weighted sums. Therefore, the best job seems to be a Machine Learning Engineer.

In [555]:
def weighted_sums(top_k_jobs, popularity_weight, salary_weight, color):
    """ calculates weighted sums for top k jobs based on given weights and outputs on histograms

    Args:
        top_k_jobs (list): jobs you want to calculate weighted sum for
        popularity_weight (float): desired significance of popularity
        salary_weight (float): desired significance of salary
        color (String): desired graph color
    """

    #make subplot
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
    index = 1

    #create histograms for each job
    for job in top_k_jobs:
        #make new data set with removed outliers
        temp_df = remove_outliers("salary", df[df["job_title"] == job], .25, .75)
        popularity = [len(temp_df) / len(df) for i in range(len(temp_df))]
        salary = [temp_df["salary"].tolist()[i] for i in range(len(temp_df))]
        vectors = [popularity, salary]
    
        # Define vectors and weights
        vectors = np.array(vectors)
        weights = np.array([popularity_weight, salary_weight])
    
        # Calculate weighted sum
        weighted_sum = np.dot(weights, vectors)
     
        # Adding labels and title
        fig.add_subplot(2,5,index)
        plt.hist(weighted_sum, bins=30, color=color, edgecolor='black')
        plt.xlabel('Weighted Sum')
        plt.ylabel('Frequency')
        plt.title(f'Weighted Sums for {job} {weights}')
        index += 1
         
    # Display the plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

#display histogram of weighted sums with popularity weight = 0.5 and salary weight = 0.5
weighted_sums(top_3_engineers, 0.5,0.5,'red')
weighted_sums(top_3_scientists, 0.5,0.5,'blue')

#display histogram of weighted sums with popularity weight = 0.1 and salary weight = 0.9
weighted_sums(top_3_engineers, 0.1,0.9,'red')
weighted_sums(top_3_scientists, 0.1,0.9,'blue')

#display histogram of weighted sums with popularity weight = 0.9 and salary weight = 0.1
weighted_sums(top_3_engineers, 0.9,0.1,'red')
weighted_sums(top_3_scientists, 0.9,0.1,'blue')

Reflection¶

Interpret Results¶

Based on my various analyses, the best job for me to pursue as a CS major is a Machine Learning Engineer. Popularity summary statistics show that engineers are the 2nd most popular general job. Salary summary statistics show that engineers generally receive a higher pay than Analysts and a similar pay to Scientists. Salary linear regression shows how Engineers are predicted to have a higher increase in salary than Scientists in the future. Weighted sums show that Engineers tended to have higher weighted sums than scientists based on different weights for salary and popularity. Within the Engineer jobs, the Machine Learning Engineer had the highest weighted sums and normal distribution. The most optimal conditions for Machine Learning Engineers are working at in-person medium-sized companies.

Discussion¶

This project utilized many skills covered in this course. I gained a deeper understanding of analyzing and filtering data, using arrays, producing graphs and linear regression models, and implementing k-mean clustering. I learned how difficult it can be to conduct independent research in the real world since you are given no guidelines on how to begin or key to check your work. I also learned how effective the techniques I used are in differet contexts: arrays can be used to make quick calculations for large numerical sets of data, graphs can reveal new things about data that might not show from textual data alone, regression models can give insight to recent and future trends, and k-mean clustering can break data into related chunks. One challenge was knowing which techniques to use in different contexts. Many times, I tried to use a certain graph or algorithm, but it ended up being irrelevant to my goal. The solution for this was to solidify my goal. Once I knew that I was trying to find the most optimal CS jobs based on popularity and salary, I could focus more on specific tasks. A second challenge was going above and beyond - it was difficult to come up with complex analyses and figure out how to analyze the data set in deep ways. A solution was trial and error: by trying many different things, I figured out what worked and what didn't and built off of previous results.

Future Improvements¶

Set-up wise, improvements could be made by choosing a better dataset. While my chosen data set was complex, it had a lot of categorical data but very little numerical data. This meant that my analyses were limited. With more numerical statistics, I could perform deeper analyses and utilize more skills. Code-wise, improvements could include making a general class so that different users can find their optimal job regardless of their field. My current code is specifically tailored to my preferences.
